# Host snapshot

Every published vbench result includes a `HOST.md` next to its JSON
file. This template is the starting point — copy it, fill it in, and
include it in your submission PR.

See [`docs/reproducibility.md`](../docs/reproducibility.md) for the
host preparation steps you should run before recording these numbers.

---

## Required fields

### Hardware

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **CPU model** | _e.g. AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (Zen 4)_ |
| **Base / boost clock** | _e.g. 4.5 GHz / 5.7 GHz_ |
| **Physical cores / logical threads** | _e.g. 16 / 32_ |
| **L3 cache** | _e.g. 64 MiB_ |
| **RAM** | _e.g. 64 GiB DDR5-6000_ |
| **Disk model** | _e.g. Samsung 990 Pro 2TB_ |
| **Disk type** | _NVMe_ / _SATA SSD_ / _HDD_ |
| **Filesystem** | _e.g. ext4_ |

How to fill these in on Linux:

```bash
# CPU
lscpu | grep -E "Model name|MHz|CPU\(s\)|Thread|Core|L3"

# RAM
free -h
sudo dmidecode -t memory | grep -E "Size|Speed|Type:"

# Disk (the device the workdir lives on)
lsblk -o NAME,MODEL,TRAN,ROTA,SIZE
df -T <workdir>
```

On macOS:

```bash
sysctl -n machdep.cpu.brand_string
sysctl -n hw.physicalcpu hw.logicalcpu
sysctl -n hw.memsize
diskutil info / | grep -E "Device / Media Name|Protocol|Solid State"
```

### Software

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **OS distro** | _e.g. Ubuntu 24.04.1 LTS_ |
| **Kernel** | _e.g. Linux 6.8.0-45-generic_ |
| **rustc** | _e.g. rustc 1.94.1 (e408947bf 2026-03-25)_ |
| **vbench version** | _git SHA, e.g. `4f9cab0`_ |
| **vbench install method** | _e.g. cargo install --git ... --rev <sha>_ |
| **DB under test** | _e.g. strata 0.6.1_ |
| **DB install method** | _e.g. curl -fsSL https://stratadb.org/install.sh \| sh_ |

How to capture these:

```bash
. /etc/os-release && echo "$PRETTY_NAME"
uname -a
rustc --version
vbench --version
git -C $(dirname $(which vbench))/.. rev-parse HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo "(installed via cargo, no git checkout)"
strata --version  # or whichever DB
```

### Tuning

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **CPU governor** | _performance / powersave / schedutil_ |
| **Turbo enabled** | _yes / no_ |
| **Swap** | _on / off_ |
| **Page cache dropped before run** | _yes / no_ |
| **Other workload on the box** | _none / list_ |

Linux:

```bash
cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu0/cpufreq/scaling_governor
cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/intel_pstate/no_turbo 2>/dev/null \
    || cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpufreq/boost 2>/dev/null \
    || echo "(unknown)"
swapon --show
ps -eo pid,pcpu,pmem,comm --sort=-pcpu | head -5
```

### Run methodology

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Number of measurement runs** | _e.g. 3 (after 1 discarded warm-up)_ |
| **Statistic reported** | _median by serial_latency_p99_ / _best of N_ / _single run_ |
| **Spread (min / max)** | _e.g. p99 ranged 9.8–11.2 ms_ |
| **Run dates** | _e.g. 2026-04-08 14:32 UTC – 14:51 UTC_ |

If reporting a single number from multiple runs, the spread row is
where you disclose how variable the underlying measurements were.
This is what makes the result honest.

---

## Optional but encouraged

- **Cooling**: stock cooler / AIO / custom loop / laptop fan
- **Form factor**: desktop / server / laptop / cloud
- **Cloud instance type**: e.g. `c7g.4xlarge` (and the AZ if it's
  performance-relevant)
- **Virtualisation**: bare metal / KVM / VMware / Docker / WSL2
- **Power profile**: AC / battery / locked-to-X-watts
- **Anything else weird**: thermal throttling observed, BIOS
  settings, undervolting, ECC RAM, NUMA topology

